metadata.name: glory hole$ #77
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Once and Future Cities #112
metadata.description:
When I was a kid I used to take apart broken electronic devices and look at the circuits, especially those with lots of good-sized components. As a scifi fan, I played with them imagining they were models of futuristic cities. For this piece I wanted to turn those memories of my childhood fantasies into glowing cyberpunk metropolises that resemble circuitry and are digital art made by computer circuits.

On the technical side, I used shaders to procedurally create the geometries and the textures. These geometries do not have vertex data like usual 3D, but are defined by mathematical functions, the so called "implicit surfaces". For each pixel a vector is constructed whose direction is used to make a simulated "scanning ray" that march step by step towards the scene, testing if it collides or not with any surface, and thus calculating the color that pixel should have. This technique is called raymarching and in this case the surface that defines the geometry is a height map.

For the procedural texture I used a formula that I discovered some years ago, a fractal of the kleinian family, in this case the square cousin version that produces patterns that look somewhat like circuits and that I have already used in other productions.

Finally there is the post processing shader, for which I developed a noisy bloom effect and a depth of field algorithm that receives from the main shader the distance from the camera for each pixel using the alpha channel.

The variations are achieved with the parameters sent to the shader and used by the hash functions that set the position and shape of the buildings, the different perspectives, the colors and patterns of the procedural textures, and the gradient of the sky.

Best viewed full screen. Also it will adapt to any aspect ratio.

In live mode:

Press 'S' to save a 3840x2160 image (16:9) 
Press 'W' to save a 3840x1080 image (32:9)

This project is GPU demanding and not intended to be run on mobile devices or low end hardware. Specially high res image generation, that is likely to fail on low end GPU's.

metadata.name: Xel I-II #5
metadata.description:
Weâ€™ve always known wallet addresses as strings of letters and numbers, Dry, soulless data, yet always present.
But what if this presence could breathe?

In the enhanced, living version of "Season One", we revisit that same idea, transforming the blockchainâ€™s most essential elements into evolving pixelated lifeforms.
Each artwork is still generated from the wallet address (`fxminter`) and the tokenâ€™s hash (`fxhash`), but the project pulses with a new kind of energy this time.

### Whatâ€™s new in this evolved version:

ðŸ•° A Magical Clock
A real-time clock has been embedded into the artwork. One that only ticks forward with each new mint.
Each minted token captures a unique minute in time, held eternally by its collector.
This enchanted clock is not merely decorative. It holds a secret that will only be fully unveiled in "Season Two".

ðŸ§© A Fragment of the Bigger Picture
Alongside the creature, every mint now receives a Roman numeral representing its mint number and a coordinate, marking its position in a hidden puzzle.
Each token is a piece of a larger design; together, these fragments will reconstruct the gateway to the next season.

ðŸ§¬ Multiple Perspectives, One Identity
The core pixel creature, still generated uniquely from your wallet and hash, now appears in three views:

* a breathing 2D form rendered in real time,
* a puzzled isometric shape,
* and a miniature preview of the final Season Two puzzle form, hinting at whatâ€™s to come.
  Your identity is no longer shown from a single angle, itâ€™s a multidimensional expression.

ðŸŽ¨ Colors from the Hash, Signatures from the Wallet
Like in the original version, all color palettes are derived directly from the hash. No two are alike.
And, as always, your wallet address is subtly signed beneath the artwork, a permanent mark of authorship.

---

This is not Season Two.
This is Season One: Alive, an evolved, living version of the original.
It preserves everything that made the first release special, but adds movement, time, spatial positioning, and hints of the next chapter.

If Season One was a spark, this version is its flame.
Only holders of these tokens will be able to step fully into Season Two and witness the transformation of their piece into its final narrative form.
Until then, this is your moment. Your pixel, your minute, your breath in the story.

Reptile ðŸ¦Ž

metadata.name: Geologic #28
metadata.description:
This series was born from a desire to depict imagined landscapes from literal building 'blocks', and the fundamental concepts of stone, sea, and sky.

Each scene pairs a subtle nod to geological processes with the fleeting mood unveiled by weather and time of day.

metadata.name: CA Panico #223
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: Swatches #73
metadata.description:
Swatches is the first generative token project by Paul Drzal.

Like photography gels scattered on the light table, the layers combine to create the composition.  A random four-color palette in varying opacities creates your swatch, hand pulled on the screen.

Colors are inspired by the bold stylized drawings of architects Wes Jones and Neil Denari.

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save your Swatch.  Zoom out and refresh to save a larger file.

metadata.name: Organic Oeuvre #12
metadata.description:
First project on FXHash.

Entirely coded in p5js.

Stochastic strokes while ensuring randomness is consistent; uses 500+ color palettes.

The pieces created by this project are dynamic and change based on the size of the viewing window ("organic"), making each viewing experience unique. 

In case you find a bug, please consider it an easter egg! Write to me on twitter if you think it's a bug and I'll send another couple your way from my reserved :)

Press s to save the image in fullscreen.

metadata.description:
As a sequel of previous collection CA Vista but with a completely different approach, CA Monti intends to explore landscape generation through the use of Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: lilium #17
metadata.description:
lilium is a remix of my piece for day 9 of genuary 2023, prompt "Plants". it uses a series of force-directed graph layouts to produce a bouquet of flowers. inspired by Jared Tarbell's Happy Place.

press "c" to capture a screenshot at the current resolution. if you'd like a screenshot at a particular resolution, you can press "r" and a prompt will appear that will let you select a fixed resolution. you can either provide a single number like "1080" or a series of two numbers like "1080x2160". you can also provide a fixed resolution in the url with the "?resolution=..."

metadata.name: The Ramp #15
metadata.description:
Even if I've recently moved to analog aesthetic, Iâ€™ve never lost interest in digital processes, when I create not fully abstract pieces, I often generate sources with 3D tools for my analog explorations.

Here Iâ€™ve explored the use of a specific analog approach to video synthesis: the ramps. And I've used the concept of modulation, which can be translated to: altering the outcome of a function through the output of another function.

You can read further about the creation process in this article I wrote: https://esnho.github.io/from-ramps-to/
